05176nam a2200673Ia 9783111081700DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831110817007 a10.1515/97831110817002doi  a(DE-B1597)641643  a(OCoLC)1408682418  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE04a306.850941 aEibach, Joachim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFragile Families :bMarriage and Domestic Life in the Age of Bourgeois Modernity (1750-1900) /cJoachim Eibach. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (IX, 293 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tChapter 1 Fragile Families? Stylish Staging and Everyday Disorder -- tChapter 2 Research and Sources -- tChapter 3 Love and a House of His Own: The Peasant Ulrich Bräker Seeks a Wife -- tChapter 4 Pious Everyday Life in the Bailiwick and the Patrician Milieu: Henriette Stettler-Herport -- tChapter 5 Bourgeois Marriage and Open Domesticity: Ferdinand and Caroline Beneke -- tChapter 6 The Parsonage as Labyrinth: Ursula and Abraham Bruckner-Eglinger -- tChapter 7 A Traveling Journeyman’s Home: Friedrich Anton Püschmann -- tChapter 8 Marital Crisis and Social Decline Among the Petite Bourgeoisie: Barbara and Johann Baumgartner -- tChapter 9 Growing Up Among the Proletariat: Friedrich Engels’ Report and Adelheid Popp -- tChapter 10 From a Bourgeois Family to an Artists’ Marriage: Paula Becker and Otto Modersohn -- tChapter 11 The Family: Decline or Resilience? -- tList of Figures -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Persons -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the era of bourgeois modernity (1750–1900), the family is as valued as it is vulnerable. It constitutes a community of care, conflict, and emotion. Time and again, it is evoked as a bond of love as well as a moral institution. Yet both love and morality are fragile. A more detailed exploration reveals that domestic life during this period was much more colorful, open, and dynamic – and also more prone to crisis – than one might expect given the vaunted view of the family that characterized the heyday of the bourgeoisie. This book rewrites the history of the modern family. Self-narratives – primarily diaries – written by members of eight families from Germany, Switzerland, and Austria serve as sources for this research. The focus extends far beyond the bourgeoisie. With a micro-historical eye, the author reconstructs family histories from the peasant milieu to the patrician elite, from the parsonage to the educated bourgeoisie; he considers the domestic life of a journeyman craftsman, a couple’s descent from the ranks of the petite bourgeoisie, the effects of an itinerant childhood among the proletariat, and the strain of being caught between a bourgeois family and artistic individuality. Many of these aspects point beyond bourgeois modernity to the family in our time.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024)1 aJones Nelson, Alissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z978311117578208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG0 cEPUBz97831110821580 cprintz978311108088840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783111